The paper deals with the expressive power of deep learning architectures, specifically convolutional networks, which are commonly used in computer vision (cs.CV) and natural language processing (cs.CL). The paper also uses tools from measure theory and matrix algebra, which are relevant to numerical analysis (cs.NA) and information theory (cs.IT). Additionally, the paper discusses the representation of data using tensor factorizations, which is relevant to data science (cs.DS). Overall, the most likely sub-category is cs.LG (Machine Learning), followed by cs.NA, cs.IT, cs.CV, and cs.DS.
